# Public Tool Page Rules

Every public tool page should prioritize utility first.

The tool interface must appear above the fold.

A standard tool page should include:
- tool interface
- short explanation
- how to use
- examples
- formula, methodology, parser rules, or assumptions where relevant
- common use cases
- FAQ section
- related tools
- breadcrumbs
- schema markup
- last reviewed date

Do not create a tool page that is only SEO text without a working tool.

Public tool pages should be generated from the tool registry whenever practical.

Each tool component should be reusable and isolated from page layout where practical.

Use docs/03-public-tool-page-spec.md and docs/04-tool-registry-spec.md as detailed references.
